clinicalDescription: Overview: Slower than normal heart rate. Adults at rest usually beat between 60 and 100 times a minute. Bradycarida is fewer than 60 beats per minute. Depends on age and physical condition. Presentation: near-fainting or fainting, dizzy, fatigure, SOB, chest pain, confusion Assessment: Symptoms and history, EKG, or Holter monitor Plan: Borderline or occasional bradycardia may not require treatment. Change in medications, pacemaker Prognosis: Bradycardia can be treated and cured.
